One continent in particular is on edge as the world gears up to fight the COVID-19 epidemic.

So far, no new cases have been confirmed in 54 countries, but World Health Organization's director of emergency operations in Africa, Michel Yao, has warned that it is only a matter of time before a case is confirmed and an outbreak is "imminent" .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
This is because of the relatively limited virus detection capacity in Africa and the high level of human exchange between Africa and the affected countries.

As of last week, only six laboratories in Africa, including the Pasteur Institute in Senegal and the Institute of Medical Science in South Africa, were capable of detecting the new coronavirus, the Guardian reported Monday.

Previously, 45 suspected cases, mainly from Ethiopia, Kenya, Ivory Coast, Ghana and Botswana, were reported to WHO. Of those, 35 have tested negative, and 10 are in quarantine awaiting testing. This has led to concerns about whether there have been undiscovered cases in Africa.

Peter Piot, Dean of the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, argued last week that cases were "inevitable" in Africa, but it was surprising that after outbreaks in Asia, Europe and the Americas, there are still no cases in Africa.

Thomas Breuer, epidemiologist and chief medical officer at glaxosmithkline Vaccines, agreed that there had been no reported cases in Africa and that "this is definitely not true" .

The World Health Organization Regional Office said 13 African countries were particularly at risk, mainly because of their high level of contact with people in the affected countries, the Financial Times reported Friday, such as Algeria, Angola, Ethiopia, Ghana, Nigeria, Tanzania and Zambia.

Take Ethiopia, which owns Ethiopian Airlines, Africa's largest airline. According to an African News Channel Report on the 11th, ehang flies 35 times a week to five destinations in China (Beijing, Shanghai, Hong Kong, Guangzhou and Chengdu) , carrying an average of 4,000 Chinese passengers a day to and from the two countries, about 70 per cent of those who arrive in Beijing Capital International Airport go on to other African countries.

Six African Airlines, including Kenya Airways and South African Airways, have suspended flights to and from China amid fears of an epidemic. However, egyptair has insisted that the suspension can not interrupt the spread of the epidemic, the airline will "share weal and woe. ".

Toward, the airline's chief executive, said World Health Organization had told the group that stopping flights would not help, given that cases had already been reported in other countries and that it was more important to take precautions at airports than to isolate and isolate them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Egyptair has stepped up efforts to disinfect flights

Still, the weakness of African health systems is a source of concern. Despite the fact that Africa, after the Ebola epidemic, has already acquired a certain amount of epidemic prevention facilities and experience, and has also strengthened the screening of entry points across Africa, but that does not mean Africa is "ready" to deal with a new outbreak of pneumonia.

In terms of mortality alone, Ebola's severity is significantly worse than that of NCP, with an average case fatality rate of about 50% , which ranges from 25% to 90% in previous outbreaks. But Zaire Ebolavirus is mainly transmitted by contact, with symptoms generally evident, and the new coronavirus can also be transmitted by droplets, even in asymptomatic individuals.

Michelle, World Health Organization's director of emergency operations in Africa, said the main challenges facing Africa were the lack of testing kits and the limited capacity of hospitals.

He says the lack of reagents is slowing down the pace of diagnosis in African countries. Previously, suspected cases of African countries mostly sent test samples to Senegal, South Africa and even countries sent samples to Paris.

At the same time, most hospitals in Africa do not have the capacity to receive large numbers of critically ill patients. "with the exception of big countries like Kenya and South Africa, most countries have very limited intensive care facilities, " Michelle said, "there may be only 10 beds in a hospital for intensive care. If there are a large number of critically ill patients, it will be a big challenge. "

As WHO's executive director for Emergency Health Planning, Michael Ryan, pointed out at Monday's press conference, "given that 90 to 100 per cent of patients require supplemental oxygen, 20 to 25 per cent require intensive care, and 5 to 10 per cent use mechanical means to assist or replace spontaneous breathing, that would put a tremendous strain on the health system. "

As a result, Michelle said, the next priority for African countries is still to detect cases as early as possible to stop the spread of the epidemic.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The African Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said all suspected cases had been tested negative as of Wednesday

The African CDC says medical centers around the world are on "high alert. ". This week, the number of African countries able to test for the new coronavirus increased to 15, including those at greater risk. More testing labs will be set up and operational in other African countries.

Who is shipping diagnostic kits to 29 laboratories in Africa. Over the weekend, the African Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also held a workshop in Senegal for scientists from 15 countries and distributed diagnostic tools, including test kits. Next week, South Africa will host training for 25 other countries, says John  Johan, director of the African Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Kenghison said there was a suggestion that insufficient testing facilities had led to undiscovered cases, and that improved testing would encourage more people with suspected symptoms to report their cases to health care.

"If you can reduce the unit of turnaround time from 'days' to 'hours, ' then people with suspected symptoms are more likely to report their illness and get tested, " says Kengesong, "But if you isolate someone for a few days, people tend not to report it. There are a lot of countries in Africa that are now able to test for the virus, and maybe in the next few weeks there will be a confirmed case. Time will tell. "

But Michelle said the non-governmental Organization, Médecins Sans Frontières Sans Fronti res and Samaritan's Purse, are providing the technical help needed to set up treatment centers, a conference call between regional partners will also be held this week.

"If there are a large number of cases, we hope that ngos can help increase the capacity to treat them, provide equipment such as oxygen cylinders and suction machines, and they have the ability to deploy treatment centres in a short time, " Michelle said.
